üìò Security Concepts ‚Äì PG-DITISS (Aug 2025)
Session 19: Physical Security & Penetration Testing Methodologies
üîπ BASIC MCQs (10)
1. Physical security mainly protects against:
A. Malware
B. Unauthorized physical access
C. SQL Injection
D. Network sniffing

2. Physical security is required to protect:
A. Only data
B. Only people
C. Assets, infrastructure, and personnel
D. Only networks

3. Which is an example of physical security control?
A. Firewall
B. IDS
C. CCTV camera
D. Encryption

4. Physical security threats include:
A. Phishing
B. Fire and theft
C. SQL Injection
D. XSS

5. The primary goal of physical security is to ensure:
A. Availability of hardware
B. Confidentiality of passwords
C. Integrity of data
D. Network speed

6. Penetration testing is performed to:
A. Patch systems
B. Identify exploitable vulnerabilities
C. Monitor logs
D. Improve UI

7. Penetration testing simulates:
A. Normal users
B. Real attacker behavior
C. Network admins
D. Auditors

8. Which is NOT a physical security mechanism?
A. Biometric access
B. Security guards
C. Fire suppression system
D. Antivirus

9. Physical access to servers can lead to:
A. UI issues
B. Total system compromise
C. Better performance
D. Faster boot

10. Penetration testing must be conducted with:
A. High bandwidth
B. Proper authorization
C. Antivirus disabled
D. Public access

üî∏ INTERMEDIATE MCQs (10)
11. Factors affecting physical security include:
A. Location and environment
B. Threat level
C. Building design
D. All of the above

12. Which threat is BEST mitigated by physical security?
A. DDoS
B. Insider theft
C. SQL Injection
D. XSS

13. Physical security controls are classified as:
A. Preventive, detective, corrective
B. Logical only
C. Network-based
D. Software-only

14. Tailgating is a physical security attack involving:
A. Malware
B. Following authorized personnel
C. Password cracking
D. Network spoofing

15. Penetration testing methodology usually begins with:
A. Exploitation
B. Reconnaissance and planning
C. Reporting
D. Patching

16. Which testing approach gives attacker‚Äôs perspective?
A. White-box
B. Black-box
C. Code review
D. Static testing

17. Penetration testing differs from vulnerability scanning because it:
A. Only detects issues
B. Actively exploits vulnerabilities
C. Runs automatically
D. Generates reports only

18. Metasploit framework is mainly used for:
A. Packet sniffing
B. Exploitation and penetration testing
C. Password storage
D. Log analysis

19. Physical security failures MOST directly affect:
A. Availability
B. Confidentiality
C. Integrity
D. All of the above

20. Penetration testing reports should include:
A. Only tool output
B. Exploits without fixes
C. Findings, impact, and recommendations
D. Source code

